<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06178050 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06178050 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  COMPANY; EARNINGS; INCREASE; EMPLOYEE; HOLIDAY; REWARD  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  For their good work, the employees of 3Com Corp. are getting an extendedFourth of July holiday -- in fact, they are getting the whole week off.;   The Santa Clara networking company, which last quarter shifted its businessstrategy and posted a $40 million loss, promised workers a paid day off foreach of three sales and financial goals they met.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PROFIT YIELDS PAID HOLIDAY AT 3COM  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Earnings  </MEMO><TEXT>     The company made all of them, so about 2,000 workers will get extra paidvacation for the three days leading up to July 4, which is a Thursday. Thenext day was already a free day for most of them.;    Key offices, such asthose involved in customer support, will remain open during the week.;    OnTuesday, 3Com reported fourth-quarter sales of $92.8 million, down 20 percentfrom $116 million the year before. Profits were $3.2 million, or 12 cents ashare, down 55 percent from $7.3 million last year.;    Because of the largethird-quarter loss linked to the business change, 3Com had a loss for the yearof $27.6 million, compared with a $20.5 million profit last year. Sales were$398 million, down 5 percent from $419 million.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff Report  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910626  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  192  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday June 26, 199100178050,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>